      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling Property Held in a Family Trust or Company in Queensland
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Property held in a trust or company structure involves different signing requirements, different tax treatment, and planning that needs to start well before listing day.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>A meaningful number of investment properties and family homes across Brisbane's inner east are owned not by individuals directly but by family trusts or private companies. These structures were typically set up for asset protection, tax planning, or estate planning purposes, often years or decades before the property comes to be sold. When the time does come to sell, the process looks similar on the surface but involves enough differences in signing requirements, tax treatment, and pre-sale planning that sellers in these structures need to be aware of what is different before they appoint an agent.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why property ends up in a trust or company</h2>
      <p>Family trusts, typically discretionary trusts, have been a widely used structure for holding investment and business assets in Australia for decades. The appeal historically included flexibility in distributing income to beneficiaries on lower marginal tax rates, asset protection from business creditors, and succession planning benefits. Private companies have been used similarly, sometimes as the trustee of a family trust and sometimes as direct property owners in their own right.</p>

      <p>The structure that made sense when the property was acquired does not always produce the most tax-efficient outcome when the property is sold. Understanding the differences between individual ownership, trust ownership, and company ownership for capital gains tax and main residence purposes is essential before you go to contract.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How selling works when the owner is a family trust</h2>
      <p>When a property is held by a discretionary (family) trust, the trustee is the legal owner of the property and therefore the vendor on the contract. Individual beneficiaries do not sign as vendors. The contract will identify the trustee in their capacity as trustee of the trust, for example: "John Smith as Trustee of the Smith Family Trust".</p>

      <p>Buyers' solicitors will routinely ask to review the trust deed to confirm that the trustee has the authority to sell trust assets. This is standard practice, not unusual scrutiny. Having the trust deed available from the start of the conveyancing process avoids unnecessary delay. If the trust has a corporate trustee, that company's directors will sign on behalf of the trustee company.</p>

      <p>The formal authority to sell comes from the trust deed itself: most properly drafted discretionary trust deeds give the trustee broad powers to deal with trust property, including selling it. If your deed is unusual or restrictive, your solicitor needs to review it carefully before you list.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Capital gains tax and family trusts: what sellers need to know</h2>
      <p>The tax treatment of a capital gain arising from a trust property sale is one of the most significant differences from individual ownership, and one that frequently catches sellers by surprise.</p>

      <p>A family trust does not pay capital gains tax directly in the same way an individual does. Instead, the capital gain flows through to the beneficiaries, who include it in their own personal tax returns for the relevant financial year. The critical point is that individual beneficiaries who are Australian residents can access the 50% CGT discount personally, provided the property has been held for more than 12 months. This means the tax treatment of the gain can vary significantly depending on which beneficiaries receive the distribution and what their other income is in that financial year.</p>

      <p>Timing the distribution of the capital gain across beneficiaries with lower income in a particular year requires planning before the property is sold. Once the contract is exchanged and the sale completes, the flexibility to move income between beneficiaries is fixed by what happened in the trust accounts for that financial year. Speaking with your accountant before you appoint an agent, let alone before you sign a contract, is not optional. The tax planning window closes the moment settlement occurs.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The main residence exemption does not apply to trusts</h2>
      <p>This is the point that surprises sellers the most. The main residence CGT exemption, which allows individuals to sell their home free of capital gains tax if it has been their principal place of residence, is not available for property held in a trust or company structure.</p>

      <p>It does not matter that the beneficiaries of the trust have lived in the property as their home for many years. The exemption belongs to individual taxpayers for property they own in their own names. Because the property is owned by the trustee, not by the individuals personally, the exemption cannot be accessed.</p>

      <p>For sellers who have been living in a trust-owned property as their home, the capital gain is fully assessable (with the 50% discount available if the asset has been held for more than 12 months), rather than being exempt. The tax liability on a property that has grown significantly in value over many years can be substantial. This is a conversation that absolutely needs to happen with a tax accountant well before you decide to sell.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Selling via a company structure</h2>
      <p>Where a property is held directly by a private company rather than a trust, the company is the vendor. The company's director or directors sign the contract on behalf of the company. As with a trust, the buyer's solicitor will want to confirm the director has authority to sign and that no other approvals are required by the company's constitution or shareholders.</p>

      <p>The key tax difference for companies is that a company does not receive the 50% CGT discount at all, regardless of how long the asset has been held. The full capital gain is assessable at the company tax rate, currently 25% for small companies meeting the base rate threshold, or 30% for companies above it. Compared with an individual selling after more than 12 months of ownership and accessing the 50% discount at their personal marginal rate, the company tax outcome on a large capital gain is often significantly less favourable.</p>

      <p>This is why many sellers who have had property in a company structure for estate planning or asset protection purposes need specialist tax advice before selling. In some cases, there are structuring options that can be explored before the sale. In others, the structure simply produces the outcome it produces, and the planning involves how to best manage the resulting tax liability.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Foreign resident capital gains withholding</h2>
      <p>If the trust or company has foreign resident controllers or beneficiaries, foreign resident capital gains withholding may apply. This requires the buyer to withhold a portion of the purchase price and pay it to the ATO unless the trustee or company obtains a clearance certificate confirming the withholding does not apply. For sales above the relevant threshold, this is another pre-sale step that needs to be organised before you go to contract. Your accountant and solicitor can advise on whether this is relevant to your structure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers in trust or company structures should do first</h2>
      <p>The process of selling a property held in a trust or company is not dramatically different from an individual sale in terms of what the market sees. The property is marketed the same way, the campaign runs the same way, and the contract process is largely the same. The differences are in the signing structure and in the tax and planning requirements that need to be managed before you reach contract.</p>

      <p>The practical steps before listing are: review the trust deed or company constitution with your solicitor to confirm signing authority; speak with your accountant about the likely capital gain, how it will be treated given your structure, and what distribution or timing decisions need to be made; confirm whether foreign resident withholding applies; and make sure your agent is briefed on who will be signing and in what capacity so there are no delays when a buyer is ready to proceed.</p>

      <p>Sellers who do this groundwork early move through the sale process cleanly. Those who leave it until after a buyer has signed a contract often find themselves managing time pressure on issues that should have been resolved before the campaign started.</p>

